node.statement: CASE 2 - Analysis of g_2 on g_1-orbit blocks. The g_1-orbit {B, g_1(B), ..., g_1^{r-1}(B)} partitions supp(g_1) = {1, 3, 4, 6, a_1, ..., a_n}. LOCATING ELEMENTS: Point 1 is in some block g_1^j(B) for some j. Point 4 is in some block g_1^l(B). CONSIDER g_2: supp(g_2) = {1, 2, 4, 5, b_1, ..., b_k}. Points 1 and 4 are both in supp(g_1) intersect supp(g_2). SUB-CASE A: If 1 and 4 are in the SAME g_1-orbit block (say both in g_1^j(B)), then g_1^j(B) contains {1, 4} and intersects supp(g_2) in at least {1, 4}. If g_2 fixes g_1^j(B), then by Lemma 11.2, supp(g_2) is contained in g_1^j(B). This block then contains {1, 2, 4, 5, b_i}. Now apply reasoning from Case 1.
